04549nam a22007695i 9780231536547DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013016126  a(OCoLC)999365124  a97802315365477 a10.7312/holl161862doi  a(DE-B1597)458944  a(OCoLC)979776660  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aTX724.5.C5bH64713 2014 4aTX724.5.C5bH64713 2015 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a641.59512231 aHöllmann, Thomas O., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Land of the Five Flavors :bA Cultural History of Chinese Cuisine /cThomas O. Höllmann. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b‹B›B&W Illus.: ‹/B›48.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aArts and Traditions of the Table: Perspectives on Culinary History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter One. Rice Doesn’t Rain from Heaven -- tChapter Two. A Taste of Harmony -- tChapter Three. Fire, Ice, and Flavor -- tChapter Four. A Culinary Cosmos -- tChapter Five. Heavenly Dew -- tChapter Six. Regulations and Conventions -- tChapter Seven. The Tavern of Eternal Happiness -- tChapter Eight. Epilogue -- tAppendix -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRenowned sinologist Thomas O. Höllmann tracks the growth of food culture in China from its earliest burial rituals to today's Western fast food restaurants, mapping Chinese cuisine's geographical variations and local customs, indigenous factors and foreign influences, trade routes, and ethnic associations. Höllmann details the food practices of major Chinese religions and the significance of eating and drinking in rites of passage and popular culture. He enriches his narrative with thirty of his favorite recipes and a selection of photographs, posters, paintings, sketches, and images of clay figurines and other objects excavated from tombs.Höllmann's award-winning history revisits the invention of noodles, the role of butchers and cooks in Chinese politics, debates over the origin of grape wines, and the causes of modern-day food contamination. He discusses local crop production, the use of herbs and spices, the relationship between Chinese food and economics, the influence of Chinese philosophy, and traditional dietary concepts and superstitions. Citing original Chinese sources, Höllmann uncovers fascinating aspects of daily Chinese life, constructing a multifaceted compendium that inspires a rich appreciation of Chinese arts and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCooking, Chinese. 0aManners and customs. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aMargolis, Karen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/holl1618640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231536547423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231536547.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK